(b) Explain the purpose of any two file management system calls

1. open()

Opens an existing file or creates a new file.
Returns a file descriptor used for future operations.
2. write()
Writes data from memory to a file.
Returns the number of bytes written.
(c) C-based system call sequence to create a file, write a student name, and close it. 
#include <fcntl.h>
#include <unistd.h>
int main() {
    int fd;

    fd = creat("student.txt", 0644);

    write(fd, "John\n", 5);

    close(fd);

    return 0;
}
Question 3 
(a) List the system calls required to copy one file to another. 
Required system calls:
open()
read()
write()
close()
(b) Explain the purpose of any two system calls.)
read()
Reads data from a file into memory.
write()
Writes data from memory into another file.
(c) C-based system call sequence to copy one file to another.
#include <fcntl.h>
#include <unistd.h>

int main() {
    int source, destination;
    char buffer[100];
    int bytes;

    source = open("input.txt", O_RDONLY);
    destination = creat("output.txt", 0644);

    while ((bytes = read(source, buffer, sizeof(buffer))) > 0) {
        write(destination, buffer, bytes);
    }

    close(source);
    close(destination);

    return 0;
}
Question 4 (10 Marks)
(a) State the purpose of fork() and exec() system calls.

fork()

Creates a new child process.
The child is a copy of the parent process.

exec()

Replaces the current process with a new program.
The process ID remains the same.
(b) Explain the role of the wait() system call. 
wait() makes the parent process wait until the child process finishes execution.
It prevents zombie processes and ensures proper synchronization.
(c) System call sequence using fork(), exec(), and wait(). (4 Marks)
#include <stdio.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <sys/wait.h>

int main() {
    pid_t pid;

    pid = fork();

    if (pid == 0) {
        execl("/bin/ls", "ls", NULL);
    } else {
        wait(NULL);
        printf("Child process completed.\n");
    }

    return 0;
}
